HEPASTITIS G - BRAZIL (3)
==========================
[1]
Date: Sat, 2 Mar 1996 20:30:43 +1100 (EST)
To: jack.woodall@wadsworth.ph.albany.edu
From: profpuk@werple.net.au (Len Moaven)
Subject: HGV
G'day Jack
Hepatitis G virus (HGV) is endemic worldwide. Isolates from all over the
world have been described, including South America (mainly in abstracts at
meetings). May I draw fellow ProMEDers to three excellent reviews (!), the
latter two describing cases in Australia:
Moaven LD, Locarnini SA. Hepatitis G virus and the GB agents. International
Antiviral News 1995; 3 (10): 164-166
Moaven LD, Bowden DS, Locarnini SA. Hep G virus and the hep GB viruses.
Todays Life Sciences (Australia) 1995; 7(11): 24-28
Bowden DS, Moaven LD, Locarnini SA. New hepatitis viruses: are there enough
letters in the alphabet? Medical Journal of Australia 1996; 164: 87-89
I guess HGV belongs to that very large group of emerging viruses that have
only recently been described because of new techniques to isolate them. I
would speculate that HGV has been around along time - like one of its
closest relatives hepatitis C virus. However, I would argue, that with the
advent of widespread injecting drug use, invasive medical procedures
etcetera HGV (and HCV) are also re-emerging pathogens.
Kind regards
Len
Len Moaven
Senior Registrar in Virology
